Overview: The original Hermes scout 'Mech rapidly developed a poor reputation. Plagued by electronic glitches and oft-criticized for its lack of firepower or armor, manufacturing for the 'Mech ceased, and Irian's lines fell silent. The start of the Succession Wars, however, would create a massive demand for BattleMechs of any sort; Irian, instead of restarting their Hermes line as-is, would rework the chassis into the heavier, slower, and tougher Hermes II. Though early tests involving an advanced torso-mounted autocannon failed, Irian quickly redesigned the Hermes II to use a more reliable Oriente autocannon placed in one of the arms. The reliable 'Mech would rapidly become one of the main heavy scouts of the FWLM, serving in numbers that few other designs could match.

Capabilities: With enough speed to stay ahead of most Free Worlds formations, the Hermes II carries decent firepower for its role. Seven and a half tons of armor keep the Hermes II well-protected, and it can outlast many other scouts on the field. The Hermes II uses many reliable and well-made systems; its E.A.R communications system is extremely advanced, able to connect to communications satellites and hard to track by enemy monitoring systems. The autocannon is durable and rarely malfunctions, and the flamer serves well as a utility weapon and as a means for the Hermes II to break visual contact with enemy forces.

Deployment: As an Irian design, the Hermes II mostly serves within FWLM forces. It has served there for centuries, and massive production lines ensure large numbers of the 'Mech enter service every year. Created as an export variant, the HER-4K "Hermes III" (not to be confused with the lighter Hermes of the same name) mounts twin large lasers instead of its standard firepower. The formation of the Free Rasalhague Republic spread the design to this new state, though deployment would not spread farther and would instead solely remain within these two factions.

# Fluff Date: 2026-02-14 18:58:16
overview:<p>The Hermes II was introduced in 2798 by Irian BattleMechs Unlimited as a heavier successor to the original Star League-era Hermes. Designed as a heavy scout for the Free Worlds League Military, the forty-ton 'Mech combined respectable firepower with superior armor protection and reliable communications capabilities, filling a critical reconnaissance role in the post-Star League era. Early prototypes suffered from a flawed autocannon placement spread across the center torso, prompting a temporary laser-armed replacement while engineers consolidated the weapon into its final mounting.</p><p>The design earned the nickname "Old Reliable" for its exceptional ease of field maintenance, making it one of the most serviceable medium 'Mechs of its time. Production continued throughout the Succession Wars and beyond, with the Hermes II becoming a signature design of House Marik's military forces. The distinctive wing-like protrusions on the 'Mech's ankles, often mistaken for heat sinks, are purely cosmetic elements linking the design to its Hermes predecessor.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Hermes II excels in restrictive terrain such as cities and forests, where its combination of speed, armor, and firepower gives it decisive advantages over lighter scouts. The Oriente autocannon provides reliable long-range firepower, while the Irian Weapons Works medium laser handles anti-'Mech duties at closer ranges. The Olympian flamer serves both anti-infantry purposes and enables the 'Mech's signature escape tactic, igniting surrounding terrain to blind enemy thermal sensors and discourage pursuit through the resulting inferno.</p><p>Seven and a half tons of Riese armor provides protection superior to most light 'Mechs the Hermes II is likely to encounter, allowing pilots to trade fire with enemy scouts or survive initial contact with heavier opponents long enough to withdraw. The Hermes 240 engine delivers a top speed of 97 kilometers per hour, sufficient to stay ahead of most pursuit.</p><p>The heart of the design is its Irian E.A.R. communications system, capable of direct satellite uplinks and tight-beam data bursts. This advanced system requires considerable surface area on the chassis, but grants reconnaissance teams exceptional coordination capabilities that have made the Hermes II invaluable for intelligence-gathering operations throughout its service history.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced in 3025, the Hermes III emerged when Kuritan engineers at Ostmann Industries recognized the potential in imported Hermes II chassis. The resulting design replaced all original weaponry with a pair of Tronel III large lasers and additional heat sinks, creating an energy-focused configuration that eliminated ammunition dependency at the cost of punishing heat buildup. The HER-4K proved popular within Draconis Combine and Free Rasalhague Republic forces, where it served as a rugged scout throughout the latter Succession Wars era. This variant was actually a serviceable downgrade from the earlier HER-2R, having lost the double heat sinks that made sustained laser fire manageable.</p>

history:<p>The Hermes II emerged from Irian BattleMechs Unlimited's massive production capacity during the military buildup following Kerensky's Exodus. Based on Star League-era Hermes schematics, the heavier design addressed the need for a more survivable scout platform. Production remained almost exclusively within the Free Worlds League throughout the Succession Wars, with only battlefield salvage and occasional mercenary sales bringing the design to other realms.</p><p>The Dark Shadows scout battalion, founded by Captain Janos DeVille in 3006, became closely associated with the Hermes II and its Mercury variant. Operating under SAFE's intelligence directorate, Dark Shadows units pioneered many of the reconnaissance tactics that defined the chassis's doctrine. DeVille later relinquished command to Captain Margarita Luhenson before rejoining the Fusiliers of Oriente, where he served during Duke Anton's revolt.</p><p>The Concord of Kapteyn opened new markets for the Hermes II, with the Draconis Combine purchasing chassis that Kuritan engineers would transform into the laser-armed Hermes III configuration. This variant proved popular enough to cement the design's reputation within the DCMS reconnaissance forces, eventually spawning a separate lineage of Luthien Armor Works upgrades.</p><p>Following the Clan Invasion and the Outreach Accords, Irian leveraged recovered lostech to produce the upgraded HER-5S, featuring an endo-steel chassis and ultra-class autocannon. Elite formations like the Free Worlds Guards received priority deliveries during the FWLM's massive upgrade program, with older models cascading down through the order of battle. This widespread distribution unfortunately meant substantial numbers fell into Word of Blake hands during their subversion of Free Worlds forces, with the Hermes II seeing service on both sides of the Jihad.</p><p>Post-Jihad recovery efforts led to continued evolution, while the ilClan era brought hybrid designs incorporating Clan technology acquired through various channels. Production continues at Irian and Shiro III facilities, ensuring the Hermes II remains a fixture of Free Worlds League reconnaissance doctrine centuries after its introduction.</p>

